[% WRAPPER h3_section id = "nsbcpp" title = "nsbcpp - the not so braindead C preprocessor" %]

<p>
An extended version of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_preprocessor">C preprocessor</a> which will provide:
</p>

<ol>
<li>
<p>
Multi-line blocks
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Inner block conditionals using if/else/etc.
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
“for/while/foreach” loops
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Blocks as arguments.
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Functions
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Utility built-ins
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Objects/structs/records / <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_array">dictionaries</a>, methods, and inheritance.
</p>
</li>
</ol>

[%- END -%]

[% WRAPPER h3_section id = "more-expressive-cmake-script-lang" title = "A more expressive scripting language for CMake (and its data-model)" %]

<p>
I like <a href="https://cmake.org/">CMake</a> and find its scripting
language usable for the kind of tasks for which I need to use it. However,
a more expressive language with capabilities closer to Python 3 or Perl 5
will still likely improve the user-experience.
</p>

<p>
Note that <a href="https://github.com/vdamewood">Vincent Damewood</a> expressed
interest in implementing such a language in the future too, so you may wish
to keep him in the loop.
</p>

